title: For Sale/Trade:  HIGH STANDARD 107 MILITARY SUPERMATIC CITATION 22LR TARGET PISTOL
location: 33914 / Babcock Webb, South West Florida, Florida
postcontent:
Want to sell or trade HIGH STANDARD 107 MILITARY SUPERMATIC CITATION 22 LR. This is the push button takedown model. Includes one magazine and original box. This is the Rolls-Royce of target pistols. This is the more desirable model made in Hamden, Connecticut. Gun does show very minor signs of wear but appear normal for its age. This gun has the exact grip angle of a 1911 45ACP and make a perfect low cost training pistol.

107 Series Models

The evolutionary successor to the 106 series. This series had the frame redesigned to eliminate the plugging of the spring hole produced with the old tooling. The earliest 107 series pistols were marked "MODEL 107 / MILITARY" and the serial number on the right side of the frame. About 1972, the "MODEL 107" and "MILITARY" markings on the frame weres deleted and then later the word "MILITARY" reappeared near the end of the end of the traditional serial number series. The "MILITARY" marking is absent from the guns with the ML prefixed serial numbers.. There is no premium associated with these variations. These markings changers were not a change in design series, only a change in markings. The serial numbers of later guns produced after mid 1975 utilized a new serial numbering system. The Military models utilized a"ML" prefix on the serial number. Early production utilized the red bottomed magazines. Later guns had a blued steel bottom. The 107 series was produced from 1968 until 1981. Production at Hamden, CT 1968 to 1976. At East Hartford 1976 to 1982. Guns with serial numbers above ML 25,000 are manufactured in East Hartford. Guns before ML 29,xxx were made by the Leisure Group and guns made after ML 29,xxx were made by High Standard Inc. The serial number ranges are best estimates as of the revision date. Valued at $695 low end fair condition to $895 high end super clean. Add $200 premium for guns with boxes and accessories if factory records verify Model Number.

The 7.62x51 NATO (.308 Winchester) PMAG 20LR is a lightweight, cost effective, high reliability magazine for SR25/M110 pattern rifles featuring true 20-round capacity, constant-curve body, and snap on Impact/Dust Cover. Designed specifically for military-issue MK11/M110 rifles and mil-spec ammunition (including M118LR), the PMAG 20LR is less than half the weight of standard issue steel magazines and maintains a service life round count approximately equal to the rifle barrel itself.

Features
Optimized for use with 7.62x51 NATO (.308 Winchester) ammunition with an overall cartridge length less than 2.820", including M118LR
Additional commercial rifle compatibility includes the KAC SR25, DPMS LR308, LWRCI REPR, LaRue OBR, Bushmaster .308 ORC, LMT .308 MWS*, Remington R-25, POF P-308, JP Enterprises LRP-07, Les Baer .308, Colt LE901-16S, the new Armalite AR-10A, S&W M&P10, and others

Constant-curve internal geometry for smooth feeding

Multi-use Impact/Dust Cover keeps dust and dirt out of the magazine during storage and protects the feedlips from potential hard impact damage during transit

Textured gripping surface and flared floorplate for positive magazine handling

*NOTICE: PMAG 20LR COMPATIBILITY WITH LMT MWS RIFLE
A potential compatibility issue has come to Magpul's attention regarding the PMAG 20LR magazine when used in a limited number of 7.62 NATO caliber LMT MWS weapon systems. When the PMAG 20LR is inserted into the magazine well, some MWS rifles exhibit interference between the bolt catch and the rear of the magazine. This can cause partial engagement of the bolt catch and result in unintentional contact between the bolt carrier group and the bolt catch during normal weapon operation. Although this issue has only been reported by a very limited number of end users, Magpul has introduced a slight modification to all new production PMAG 20LR magazines to eliminate any potential for bolt catch interference, effective 5/18/2011.

title: For Sale:  COLT LE6920: To whom it may concern...
postcontent:
To whom it may concern…

	The day I was brought home was the happiest day of my life, but what was once a life of dreams and endless possibilities has turned and forsaken me. Hello, my name is COLT AR-15 5.56 NATO LE6920 and I want to be anywhere but here. 
	My owners treated me like royalty when they brought me home, they showed me to all of their friends and family bragging about "The COLT AR-15 5.56 NATO LE6920" being top of the line. Bragging about me being the "Real Deal" that I wasn't just some M-Forgery. I felt like the most important COLT LE6920 that had ever been produced. Each person that held me was in awe of my touch, my ergonomics, my aura. Each person that held me wanted to take me home always making a comment about how they had always wanted to hold one…to own one. This went on and on, I never grew tired of the sparkle in their eyes when I was brought out…like a little child on Christmas morning every time they saw me. But this all ended, and abruptly I might add. 
	My owners put me away, never firing me, never allowing me to show them what I can do. All of the perfection, all of the time and energy spent in engineering the perfect AR-15 just to put me right back in my original packaging. Why? WHY!?!? My owners went out and got themselves AK's, I mean, who's side are they on? The male has his Russian Saiga AK-74, and the female has her Egyptian Maadi AK-47. I know they have been out shooting with them too…all the time in fact. They come home smelling of gun powder laughing and retelling their stories to each other about how much fun they had and how well their AK's performed…and all of this was done right in front of me, over and over…in front of me as if I had no feelings at all.
	I can't take it anymore, I need to be freed. I need to do what I was put here to do, and thats Kill Zombies and Commies! Somebody…anybody who reads this please free me, please let me do what I was made to do. Don't let me live my life in this cardboard box to be forgotten.

title: For Sale:  1957 vintage ruger single six
postcontent:
I have a ruger single six in 22 lr that was made in 1957 that I'd like to trade or part trade.  

The good:  strong rifling, excellent shooter, and the kind of quality built into guns from the era. All steel, no plastic, no alloy, just solid straight shooting early ruger quality. 

The bad:  someone re-finished the gun. Looks like possibly cera-kote?  Don't know. It was done before I received the pistol. While its durable, I assume it kills any collector value the gun might have had, and relegates it to "shooter" status, which it does an excellent job of.  The stocks/grips aren't the greatest, but they're cheap and easy to change. 

What am I looking for?  I'm hoping to trade or part trade for a kahr (probably cw series, but open to others) in 9, 40, or 45.  Also open to ruger sr compact series, or other solid brand compacts in full size calibers (no hi-points, lorcins, cobras, etc...) and I don't need a .380.  I also like big bore six guns, and am ok with taurus, or European replicas. 
If you have other trade ideas, send them to me. I'm easy to work with, and will be polite if you do the same.  If you like the gun but want cash on my end, I'm open, but be reasonable. I can add some ammo to sweeten the deal as well. 

Prefer WA State ccl holder, and there will be a bill of sale/trade for your records and mine

title: For Sale:  LNIB Sig Sauer 556 SWAT Patrol
postcontent:
Model #R556-16B-PS-RD . This rifle is extremely new, manufactured on 2/24/2013 and purchased by me on 3/8/2013. I took it out to Long Range Alley one time and fired 120 rounds through it. As expected, not a single problem. This was my dream rifle for the longest time and I'm glad I got to own one but I'm selling it because I'm trying to get my family into a new house and would like to put the money towards that. I figure now is a good time to sell since Washington is working on the background check legislation and the time is now to buy any guns people may want without a paper trail.

This rifle is amazing. Sig hit the nail on the head with this one. For those that don't know, it's the ideal hybrid of an AK and an AR. I just read that the Philadelphia SWAT team just adopted this as their standard rifle. It uses a bolt thats basically identical to an AK47. Uses a two position piston system so when the gas port gets gunked up, you can change the position and keep on rockin, if the both get gunked up you can turn it completely off and have a bolt action rifle. Its quite amazing. It uses AR15 magazines and shoots both 556 and 223. This gun is extremely easy to clean and will make you hate cleaning your AR. 

The only thing I did to this gun is remove the A2 birdcage flash hider and replace it with a Stryker Comp from 556 Tactical here in Shreveport. It's a really cool compensator that's extremely effective and attractive. It comes in the box it shipped in with all the paperwork, blank warranty card, coupon for 20% off on Sig's website, unopened 3 pack of Ergo rail covers, small bottle of lube, and one 30 rd NHMTG magazine (scratched up but came that way, it's aluminum what do you expect). The gun features Sig's own RDSS (rotary diopter sight system) that is very much like HK's. It has 4 aperture's, CQB, 100yrd, 200yrd and 300yrd. The top rail of the receiver also has an internal rear sight that flips down and is concealed within the rail.

Any questions please ask. I'm looking for $1,550 or best offer. Like I said, I'm not hurting for money, just trying to give a boost to my dream of moving. I am flexible and I have some 20 round PMAG's that I may be willing to either sell of throw in to make a deal work.

Respond by email or text REDACTED
I'll entertain offers for trades but I'm mainly looking for cash. Making an offer couldn't hurt, I might bite. Partial trades would be a Lucid HD7 red dot (preferrably in tan), INFORCE WML light, JP silent captured buffer, PWS enhanced buffer tube, maybe a Kahr pistol in 9mm or 45, quality firearms. Anything really, worse I can do is say no.
